#cli #design #spec

> scan and recall commands for high-recall, LLM-friendly memory retrieval.

Two commands added to improve how agents load context from the memory graph.

scan <query> [--limit N]
  Broad discovery. Scores every candidate note across multiple signals (additive):
    slug exact match (case-insensitive)  100  — highest priority
    tag exact match                       60
    rel name exact match                  40
    slug partial match                    20
    tag partial match                     10
    rel name partial match                 5
    body substring match                   3  — lowest direct signal
    1-hop neighbor of a direct match       1  — expansion only
  Results sorted by score descending, trimmed to limit.
  Returns compact summaries: slug, desc, tags, edge_count, score.
  body_preview is still in the store result dict but NOT shown in CLI output —
  kept for programmatic use / future tooling.

recall <slug> [--n N]  (default N=1)
  Focused retrieval. Given a slug:
    1. Returns the full note (body, desc, tags, all edges)
    2. Returns up to N direct neighbours with full body content
  Both outgoing and incoming neighbours are included.
  Use this to load a specific topic and its immediate context into an LLM.
  Default N=1 keeps output tight; pass --n 3 or higher for broader context.

Store methods:
  store.scan(query, limit=20)  → list[{slug, desc, tags, body_preview, edge_count, score}]
  store.recall(slug, n=5)      → {note: full_note_dict, related: [full_note_dicts]} | None

SHARP EDGE: recall() updates last_recalled_at in the DB (via record_recall).
This metadata is DB-only (.eshp.db, gitignored). The eshp summarise command
surfaces recently recalled slugs — useful for agents to see what was recently in focus.

